WEBVTT

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:02.460
Thermals — how do thermals form?

00:00:03.250 --> 00:00:08.890
We have the sun, as we've already discussed — it's the engine of the weather.

00:00:09.540 --> 00:00:14.400
The sun shines on the Earth's surface and warms the air layer near the ground.

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:18.480
Accordingly, there's a slightly warmer layer of air at the ground.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:20.980
That's really important to understand for thermals.

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.100
When we're flying or looking for thermals, we always have to ask ourselves,

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:30.560
which air mass, or rather which ground, warms up more than the other.

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:33.080
It's always about a temperature difference.

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:36.360
It doesn't have to be warm per se — in winter we can also fly thermals.

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:43.260
If the forests, for example, are snow-free, they warm up more than a snow-covered meadow slope.

00:00:43.740 --> 00:00:45.780
So the thermals are to be found over the forest.

00:00:46.220 --> 00:00:48.680
So the temperature difference is always really important.

00:00:49.870 --> 00:00:56.900
It also has to do with the albedo effect, because some surfaces warm up more strongly than others.

00:00:56.900 --> 00:01:01.260
For example, there's a dry field that's been harvested.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:05.220
It warms up more than a green meadow that maybe is still damp.

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:08.160
So you always have to ask which surface warms up more.

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:12.120
And there's also the basic rule — the more reflective a surface is,

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:14.800
snow for example, the less it actually warms up.

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:21.440
Or a black surface, a dark surface, of course warms up a lot more,

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:24.280
because it absorbs much more heat from the sun's rays.

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:31.250
Another thing that's really important for warming is the sun's angle of incidence.

00:01:31.250 --> 00:01:32.350
Ideally, the sun's rays that we see here

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:35.370
hit a surface at a right angle.

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:38.370
That way the surface gets warmed much more strongly

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:43.800
than a surface that's tilted, where the sun's rays only hit at a shallow angle.

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:48.800
Think for example again of the polar regions and the tropical regions.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.040
That also has to do only with the angle of incidence of the sun.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:02:00.080
Accordingly, a warm air layer forms at the ground, which builds a bubble.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:04.280
And the warm air layer, when it has enough temperature difference,

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:07.380
and is released by a small trigger,

00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:10.580
detaches and starts to rise.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:13.790
You can picture it a bit like a lava lamp.

00:02:13.790 --> 00:02:15.790
This air mass stays closed.

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:16.790
That's again an air mass.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:19.970
It's an air mass with a uniform property.

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:21.970
It's warmer than the air mass around it.

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:23.970
And it rises away.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:26.560
So here we have two air masses.

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:29.560
We have the atmosphere outside, which has a certain temperature,

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:31.560
which we'll also briefly touch on.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:33.560
And the warm air layer that rises.

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:34.560
The bubble that rises.

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:37.560
And forms the thermal.

00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:40.560
You can also picture a hot-air balloon.

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:43.560
It also rises because it has warmer, warm air,

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.560
which is less dense.

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:48.560
And so the hot-air balloon rises.

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:51.800
The same is true of the thermal,

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:56.220
of this thermal bubble that rises.

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:59.220
Again, we have a certain air pressure

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:02.220
that prevails in our atmosphere.

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:04.220
We have higher air pressure in the lower region

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:06.220
than in the upper layers.

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:08.220
Now we come back to air pressure.

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:10.460
You can see, we're starting to tie things together.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:13.460
Accordingly, when a balloon like this rises —

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:16.050
some of you may know this from diving.

00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:19.050
Or with a weather balloon you see it very impressively.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:21.050
When it's down low,

00:03:21.050 --> 00:03:24.050
it has a very small volume of the gas inside it.

00:03:24.050 --> 00:03:27.050
When it rises, where the air pressure here drops,

00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:29.350
then the gas can expand more and more.

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:32.350
And so the volume increases,

00:03:32.350 --> 00:03:35.940
of the air parcel that's rising.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:38.050
And then we come to the cooling.

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:40.050
When the balloon rises,

00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:42.050
there's a decompression,

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:45.050
the pressure of the rising air parcel drops.

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:47.050
It expands, the pressure drops.

00:03:47.050 --> 00:03:51.050
And when in an air mass, or in a gas generally, the pressure drops,

00:03:51.050 --> 00:03:53.130
then the temperature decreases.

00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:55.210
You see this very impressively, for example,

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:58.260
with a compressed-air gun —

00:03:58.260 --> 00:04:00.260
when you blow air out, it's ice cold.

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:02.260
That basically only has to do with the fact

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:04.260
that the compressed air from the compressor

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:07.340
expands very quickly and cools down as a result.

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:11.670
So an air mass that expands cools down.

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:13.670
Accordingly, the opposite is also true.

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:15.670
When an air mass is compressed,

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:17.670
it warms up.

00:04:17.670 --> 00:04:19.670
You also see this in practice, for example,

00:04:19.670 --> 00:04:21.670
when you pump up a tyre.

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:23.670
When you pump up a pressurised tyre,

00:04:23.670 --> 00:04:25.670
at some point it gets really warm.

00:04:25.670 --> 00:04:27.670
And that's because you're compressing a lot of air there.

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:29.670
Always keep this picture in mind.

00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:32.670
It's really important for various meteorological phenomena,

00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:35.970
including thermals here.

00:04:35.970 --> 00:04:37.970
If you look at the numbers,

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:38.970
you can imagine

00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:40.970
that the ground starts at 20 degrees.

00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:42.970
These are just approximate numbers.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:43.970
And then it rises

00:04:43.970 --> 00:04:48.420
and the temperature decreases more and more with altitude.

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:49.420
Exactly.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:51.420
That has to do with decompression

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:54.340
and with this air mass rising.

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:56.340
In the end, if we just picture it,

00:04:56.340 --> 00:04:58.340
in the atmosphere we have

00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:00.340
a certain temperature gradient.

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:03.510
Ideally it gets colder and colder with altitude.

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:06.510
The air mass here is sitting at night, for example.

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.510
At night the air mass flows here.

00:05:08.510 --> 00:05:09.510
It's a bit warmer at ground level

00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:10.510
than higher up.

00:05:10.510 --> 00:05:12.510
On Mount Everest it's much colder

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:13.510
than down at the sea, for example,

00:05:13.510 --> 00:05:15.510
just to picture it visually.

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.510
And there you have the temperature gradient,

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:19.510
which is again a progression,

00:05:19.510 --> 00:05:20.510
a gradient,

00:05:20.510 --> 00:05:25.360
a temperature gradient of this air mass,

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:27.360
which is just sitting here.

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:29.360
And now in the morning the sun comes up,

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:32.360
the engine of the weather starts to work,

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:35.380
starts to heat up the surfaces on the ground

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:37.550
and the thermals rise away

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:38.550
and cool down.

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:40.950
And through the cooling process,

00:05:40.950 --> 00:05:44.030
the thermal usually

00:05:44.030 --> 00:05:46.030
reaches a point somewhere

00:05:46.030 --> 00:05:47.030
where it's just as cold

00:05:47.030 --> 00:05:49.030
as the surrounding air.

00:05:49.030 --> 00:05:51.030
Now here in this case, the thermal top

00:05:51.030 --> 00:05:52.030
is reached at the point

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:54.030
where the air mass is at minus two degrees.

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:56.030
And the surrounding air,

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:57.030
where you're sitting right there,

00:05:57.030 --> 00:05:59.030
is at a certain point

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:00.030
exactly as cold

00:06:00.030 --> 00:06:02.050
as the parcel that's rising.

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:03.050
Accordingly,

00:06:03.050 --> 00:06:06.050
the hot-air balloon no longer has any temperature advantage

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:08.050
and it won't rise any further.

00:06:08.050 --> 00:06:10.050
The thermal stops at a certain point.

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:12.790
Exactly,

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:15.740
that has to do with the temperature state curve,

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:16.740
as it's also called.

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:18.740
The temperature state curve describes

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:20.740
really just the atmosphere,

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:22.740
that is, the stratification of the air mass,

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:23.740
as it sits there.

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:27.480
The cooling

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:29.560
that takes place here

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.770
is also described

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:33.770
as an adiabatic process

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:35.770
or as adiabatic cooling.

00:06:35.770 --> 00:06:37.770
And there are two of them,

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:39.770
which I'll get into in a moment.

00:06:39.770 --> 00:06:41.910
And you can imagine

00:06:41.910 --> 00:06:42.910
that the surrounding air mass

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.910
has a certain state.

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:46.910
Here it's just shown a bit differently,

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:47.910
so you can picture

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:49.910
that there are two different air masses —

00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:50.910
that's really important.

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:53.910
There's very little mixing going on between them.

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:54.910
And especially the way

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:56.910
you want to learn it for the theory exam,

00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:58.930
that's the most relevant point.

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:02.070
There's also a Meteo Advanced course,

00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:05.070
where we get into thermal theory in much more detail.

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:07.070
There are also other effects there

00:07:07.070 --> 00:07:08.070
that are relevant,

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:10.070
but for the basic theory course

00:07:10.070 --> 00:07:11.070
they go way too far.

00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:14.890
Exactly,

00:07:14.890 --> 00:07:16.890
now we see the temperature decrease

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:19.220
that makes the air parcel rise.

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:21.690
And there's a second factor that comes in,

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:24.690
which for us as pilots is really very important.

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:26.690
And that's humidity.

00:07:26.690 --> 00:07:29.220
In an air parcel we have —

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:31.220
and right now in this room here too —

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.220
we have a certain proportion of water vapour.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:37.220
So we don't only have oxygen and nitrogen,

00:07:37.220 --> 00:07:40.220
but we also have a certain water-vapour content

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:42.220
in our air parcel.

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:43.220
Humidity,

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:45.220
it's variably moist.

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:46.220
Depending on

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:48.220
what kind of air mass it is.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:50.220
You can imagine,

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:51.220
with these blue dots,

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:55.320
that's the water vapour in this gas.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:58.320
And when the air parcel now rises

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:00.320
and cools down,

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:04.480
then the water vapour has less and less room,

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:06.500
you can picture it that way.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:09.500
And at some point there's the change,

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:11.500
where the air mass can no longer

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.990
absorb any more moisture.

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:19.200
And then the gaseous water vapour starts

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:22.410
to change its state of matter into liquid.

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:23.410
Liquid is relative,

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:26.410
because we usually see it as clouds.

00:08:26.410 --> 00:08:30.410
So every fog and every cloud is actually nothing other

00:08:30.410 --> 00:08:33.410
than water in the air.

00:08:33.410 --> 00:08:36.410
And really, really microscopically small water droplets.

00:08:36.410 --> 00:08:38.680
It doesn't have to be rain;

00:08:38.680 --> 00:08:40.680
it's really, really tiny droplets,

00:08:40.680 --> 00:08:41.680
which we perceive,

00:08:41.680 --> 00:08:43.680
for our eye, more like a gas.

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:47.110
But they're really water droplets in the air.

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:49.110
And then we talk about condensation.

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:51.110
The condensation level,

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:53.110
where the air mass starts to condense,

00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:55.510
the water vapour that's in there.

00:08:55.510 --> 00:08:57.510
A word we also hear again and again

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:00.390
is the relative humidity,

00:09:00.390 --> 00:09:01.390
which then increases.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:04.390
And at 100 percent of course we've reached the point

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:08.880
where the air mass can no longer absorb any more moisture.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:12.780
Exactly.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.950
Then, when the condensation process kicks in,

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:17.950
when the water vapour becomes water,

00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:20.950
so when it really turns into tiny water droplets,

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:25.340
then physically a phenomenon happens,

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:29.340
namely that when it goes from gaseous to liquid,

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:31.340
heat is released.

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:33.340
A little bit of heat is released.

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:36.380
And of course also if it were to change from liquid

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:38.380
into the solid state.

00:09:38.380 --> 00:09:40.380
Those are the three states of matter.

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:42.380
After that a little bit of heat is released,

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:45.380
a little bit of energy is released in this process.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:47.660
The other thing is the opposite of course.

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:51.820
When we have a change of state

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:54.820
from solid to liquid or from liquid to gaseous,

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:56.820
then heat is consumed.

00:09:56.820 --> 00:10:00.920
An important point in this condensation process

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:03.290
is the back-of-the-envelope calculation

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:05.300
we're just looking at here.

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:06.300
And that's important for you

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:09.410
to understand what's roughly happening here.

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:12.730
When the air mass rises, it cools down.

00:10:12.730 --> 00:10:14.730
As long as it rises dry-adiabatically,

00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:17.730
that is, without any condensation process taking place,

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:19.730
it's very simple.

00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:21.730
It's just 1 degree per 100 metres.

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:23.730
So when it rises,

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:25.780
it cools down by 1 degree per 100 metres

00:10:25.780 --> 00:10:27.790
in this thermal bubble.

00:10:27.790 --> 00:10:30.290
That's very simple.

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:32.430
You can remember that number.

00:10:32.430 --> 00:10:34.430
In the moist-adiabatic process

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:36.430
the back-of-the-envelope calculation starts.

00:10:36.430 --> 00:10:38.430
Specifically, we have the 1 degree per 100 metres

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:40.610
by which it cools.

00:10:40.610 --> 00:10:42.610
But working against that is the condensation process,

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:44.610
which always releases a bit of energy

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:46.780
in the form of heat.

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:48.780
And so here of course

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:50.780
a certain amount is subtracted

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:52.780
from those degrees per 100 metres,

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:54.780
which in the end comes out to roughly

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.780
0.65 degrees per 100 metres.

00:10:56.780 --> 00:10:59.120
The value, as you can see here,

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.120
isn't always exactly the same.

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:03.650
That has to do with the fact

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:05.650
that a warm air mass

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:07.650
can absorb more moisture

00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:09.650
than a cold one.

00:11:09.650 --> 00:11:11.650
In a warm air mass we have correspondingly

00:11:11.650 --> 00:11:13.650
more moisture that starts to condense

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:15.650
than in a colder air mass,

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:17.660
for example in polar regions.

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:19.660
So the value

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:22.000
varies a little.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
But for you it's important to know

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.400
that it's simply smaller than 1 degree.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:28.400
Here's the back-of-the-envelope calculation

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:30.400
of moist-adiabatic cooling.

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:33.020
You can remember these two numbers.

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:35.020
And now let's look at

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:38.770
what that means in practice.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:40.770
Now we see the air mass

00:11:40.770 --> 00:11:42.780
rising here below.

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:44.780
In this case a dry-adiabatic cooling

00:11:44.780 --> 00:11:46.780
with 1 degree per 100 metres.

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:48.960
At a certain point

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:50.960
the rising air mass reaches

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.230
the condensation level.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:55.230
The condensation process

00:11:55.230 --> 00:11:57.600
begins.

00:11:57.600 --> 00:11:59.600
And so the air mass cools

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:01.600
now, in this case, only by

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:03.810
0.65 degrees per 100 metres.

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:05.810
That's the moist-adiabatic process.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:07.810
That keeps going

00:12:07.810 --> 00:12:09.810
until, as we had before,

00:12:09.810 --> 00:12:11.810
the air parcel has the same temperature

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:15.550
as the surrounding air.

00:12:15.550 --> 00:12:17.550
Those are the two

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:19.550
adiabatic cooling processes

00:12:19.550 --> 00:12:21.550
you need to know.

00:12:21.550 --> 00:12:27.120
Then we have an image here maybe

00:12:27.120 --> 00:12:29.390
from practice,

00:12:29.390 --> 00:12:31.410
from flight practice.

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:33.410
You see the landscape.

00:12:33.410 --> 00:12:35.410
You have to ask yourself: where does

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:37.410
the air mass rise best?

00:12:37.410 --> 00:12:39.410
Or much more importantly: where does

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:41.410
the ground warm up the most?

00:12:41.410 --> 00:12:43.490
That's right-angled sun exposure.

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:45.490
Maybe a ground that warms up a bit more

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:47.490
than the ground around it.

00:12:47.490 --> 00:12:49.490
In this case the meadow areas

00:12:49.490 --> 00:12:51.490
certainly warm up a bit more

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:53.630
than a forest.

00:12:53.630 --> 00:12:55.630
On the south-facing slope, at some point the thermal lifts off.

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:57.630
It rises, it rises, it rises

00:12:57.630 --> 00:12:59.630
and at some point it forms

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:01.630
beautiful cumulus clouds

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:03.630
that mark the thermals.

00:13:03.630 --> 00:13:05.780
If of course we also

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:07.780
have wind on top of that,

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:09.780
if we picture a balloon

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:11.780
rising, then of course it drifts

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:13.780
into the wind, with the wind.

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:16.020
And so it's

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:18.020
a puzzle when you come here

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:20.020
for cross-country flying — where do I fly to?

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:22.020
You always have to piece together

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:24.060
where the thermal lifts off

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:27.260
and where it forms a nice little cloud.

00:13:27.260 --> 00:13:29.310
Another important point:

00:13:29.310 --> 00:13:31.840
the thermal, the thermal air mass

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.840
that rises, doesn't always have to

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:36.020
form a little cumulus cloud.

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:38.020
It can also be that the

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:40.020
temperature advantage of the thermal —

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:42.030
I'm thinking of the balloon — is exhausted,

00:13:42.030 --> 00:13:44.400
so that it has equalised,

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:46.400
before a condensation process

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.400
takes place. Then over here

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.400
there might be exactly the same — over there

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.740
exactly the same thermal, but it has

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:54.900
stopped rising before

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:56.940
it condensed. And so

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:58.940
we talk about blue thermals.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:00.940
That's the term you can remember.

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:02.940
Blue thermals are actually nothing other

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:05.790
than thermals that never condensed.

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:10.620
Right. A term for thermals

00:14:10.620 --> 00:14:12.620
that you also hear from time to time

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:14.670
is the term lee thermal.

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:16.910
We had it before — windward

00:14:16.910 --> 00:14:18.910
and leeward. The lee side,

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:20.910
the side of the mountain facing away from the wind.

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:22.910
If we picture a wind here,

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:24.910
this is the side facing away from the wind

00:14:24.910 --> 00:14:27.470
of these mountains. Maybe we have

00:14:27.470 --> 00:14:29.650
sun exposure that warms

00:14:29.650 --> 00:14:31.650
exactly these surfaces,

00:14:31.650 --> 00:14:33.650
the angle of the sun,

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:35.650
more than the other side.

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:37.650
And so the thermal lifts off best there.

00:14:37.650 --> 00:14:40.240
And so we speak of a lee thermal.

00:14:40.240 --> 00:14:42.240
So a thermal that's there at the end,

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:44.240
on the side facing away from the wind.

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:46.240
That happens of course mostly

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:48.240
when, for example, we have a north wind

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:50.240
in the Alps.

00:14:50.240 --> 00:14:52.240
Because the south side of the mountains

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:54.240
in the Alps always warms up best.

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:56.240
So south-facing slopes are best.

00:14:56.240 --> 00:14:58.240
If we now have a north wind, or a Bise,

00:14:58.240 --> 00:15:00.240
on top of that for example,

00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:02.240
then the wind comes from the north.

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:04.240
And so the lee thermal

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:06.740
is very pronounced.

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:08.740
Lee thermals usually have the property

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:10.740
of being more turbulent.

00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:12.740
So lee rotors, mechanical turbulence.

00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:14.740
You see, we're tying more and more things together.

00:15:14.740 --> 00:15:16.740
We have mechanical turbulence here

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:18.740
that of course chops up the thermal.

00:15:18.740 --> 00:15:20.740
It's a bit like a shredder

00:15:20.740 --> 00:15:22.740
that, depending on wind strength, makes the thermal

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:26.000
more turbulent.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
But usually the lee thermal is also

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.110
a bit stronger.

00:15:30.110 --> 00:15:32.110
Because the air parcels in the lee,

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:34.110
in the wind-sheltered area,

00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:36.110
could heat up for longer.

00:15:36.110 --> 00:15:38.110
And so they're much warmer

00:15:38.110 --> 00:15:40.190
than a windward thermal for example.

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:42.430
So if we had

00:15:42.430 --> 00:15:44.430
the other wind direction,

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:46.540
then the air parcel

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:48.540
gets carried away by the wind again and again.

00:15:48.540 --> 00:15:50.540
And so

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:52.540
the air mass on the windward side

00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:54.540
can't heat up as long

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:56.780
as a lee thermal.

00:15:56.780 --> 00:15:58.780
Now that's something

00:15:58.780 --> 00:16:00.780
that's already a bit advanced,

00:16:00.780 --> 00:16:02.780
but good to know.

00:16:02.780 --> 00:16:08.700
What's important is that you know

00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:11.440
what a lee thermal is.

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:13.440
Now we move on

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:15.440
from the temperature state curve —

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.440
that's really important —

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:19.970
of the air mass that rises,

00:16:19.970 --> 00:16:21.970
and we're talking about the air mass

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:23.970
that just sits there,

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:25.970
which formed during the night,

00:16:25.970 --> 00:16:27.970
just the state of the whole air mass

00:16:27.970 --> 00:16:29.970
that lies over Switzerland at this moment.

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:32.460
And from this point on

00:16:32.460 --> 00:16:34.460
we really only talk about the air mass

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:37.630
that's sitting there, not about the thermal any more.

00:16:37.630 --> 00:16:39.630
The air mass can be various things.

00:16:39.630 --> 00:16:42.030
Ideally, or normally,

00:16:42.030 --> 00:16:44.030
the warm air mass is at the bottom

00:16:44.030 --> 00:16:46.030
and it gets colder and colder

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:48.240
the higher you go.

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:50.320
For example with an unstable stratification.

00:16:50.320 --> 00:16:52.820
You can imagine that

00:16:52.820 --> 00:16:54.820
when the hot-air balloon rises,

00:16:54.820 --> 00:16:56.820
the temperature advantage

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:58.820
can be sustained for much longer,

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:00.820
because it's getting colder above,

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.820
than if we had the opposite,

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:05.060
the so-called inversion.

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:07.060
There are, with certain weather situations,

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:09.060
with high-pressure influence for example,

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:11.060
inversions,

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:13.060
the other way round,

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:15.060
where we often have cold at the bottom

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:17.060
and on the mountaintops we have very warm.

00:17:17.060 --> 00:17:19.070
You sometimes get that in winter,

00:17:19.070 --> 00:17:21.070
when there are strong inversions.

00:17:21.070 --> 00:17:23.070
In Zurich by the lake it's cold,

00:17:23.070 --> 00:17:25.070
you sit in the fog down below,

00:17:25.070 --> 00:17:27.070
and on the peaks above, while skiing

00:17:27.070 --> 00:17:29.070
it's the most beautiful, warmest weather,

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:31.070
where you can almost sit out at a table.

00:17:31.070 --> 00:17:33.470
That's a so-called inversion.

00:17:33.470 --> 00:17:36.190
And now you can imagine,

00:17:36.190 --> 00:17:38.190
when the thermal rises up into an inversion,

00:17:38.190 --> 00:17:40.190
where it often gets warmer with altitude,

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:42.190
we no longer have any temperature advantage.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:44.430
After that the air mass basically stops rising.

00:17:44.430 --> 00:17:46.430
And so we talk about

00:17:46.430 --> 00:17:48.430
a very stable stratification.

00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:50.430
That's a stable stratification,

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:52.430
with too little thermal activity to expect.

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:54.430
Very calm air masses too.

00:17:54.430 --> 00:17:56.430
You get really milky conditions.

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.430
Beautiful for hike-and-fly and so on,

00:17:58.430 --> 00:18:00.430
but not so beautiful for thermal flying.

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:03.120
Down below there's the middle range,

00:18:03.120 --> 00:18:05.120
a so-called isothermal layer,

00:18:05.120 --> 00:18:07.650
as it's called.

00:18:07.650 --> 00:18:09.650
That's when the temperature state

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:11.650
stays exactly the same with altitude.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:13.650
If we have 6 degrees in the valley below

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:15.650
and 6 degrees up on the mountain,

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.650
then that's a so-called isothermal layer,

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:19.710
a constant air stratification.

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:23.500
Exactly.

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:25.500
But the temperature state in the atmosphere

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:27.500
is definitely such that it's warm below

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:31.280
and gets colder with altitude.

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:33.360
Now there are a few exam questions here

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:35.790
about this inversion

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:37.790
or unstable air stratification etc.,

00:18:37.790 --> 00:18:39.790
where you'll see a temperature gradient

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:41.790
written out in text form —

00:18:41.790 --> 00:18:43.790
at 500 metres it's 15 degrees,

00:18:43.790 --> 00:18:45.790
at 800 metres it's 14 degrees etc.

00:18:45.790 --> 00:18:47.790
It's listed out like that.

00:18:47.790 --> 00:18:49.790
And now of course you'll often be asked,

00:18:49.790 --> 00:18:51.790
where is there a surface inversion?

00:18:51.790 --> 00:18:54.580
Then you have to think:

00:18:54.580 --> 00:18:56.580
I'm looking down here at 500 metres,

00:18:56.580 --> 00:18:58.580
and an inversion, ah,

00:18:58.580 --> 00:19:00.580
is a reversed air stratification.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:02.580
That means it gets warmer with altitude.

00:19:02.580 --> 00:19:04.580
Then you just have to read the numbers here.

00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:06.580
For example, here 1 is 15 degrees

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:08.580
and at 800 metres it's 16 degrees.

00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:10.580
That's getting warmer, that's an inversion.

00:19:10.580 --> 00:19:13.170
The same with a high-altitude inversion,

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:15.170
the same thing takes place,

00:19:15.170 --> 00:19:17.310
just at higher altitudes.

00:19:17.310 --> 00:19:19.310
Or an isothermal layer,

00:19:19.310 --> 00:19:21.310
for example here at 4, where we have 8 degrees

00:19:21.310 --> 00:19:23.310
at both altitudes —

00:19:23.310 --> 00:19:26.000
that's a constant air stratification.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.460
So that's an example exam question.

00:19:28.460 --> 00:19:31.730
Then we come to the next chapter,

00:19:31.730 --> 00:19:33.810
which is important.

00:19:33.810 --> 00:19:35.810
Here we open up the chapter on

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:37.810
cloud names, cloud shapes,

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:39.810
cloud pictures, and what that means for us.

00:19:39.810 --> 00:19:42.370
With clouds it's like this —

00:19:42.370 --> 00:19:44.670
as in this diagram,

00:19:44.670 --> 00:19:46.670
there are lots of Latin names

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:48.670
and it's sometimes very complicated

00:19:48.670 --> 00:19:50.670
to remember and to know what they mean.

00:19:50.670 --> 00:19:52.670
It's a real maze.

00:19:52.670 --> 00:19:54.720
Now we'll try to sort it out

00:19:54.720 --> 00:19:58.460
and see how it comes about.

00:19:58.460 --> 00:20:01.180
For cloud names,

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:03.180
in my head I make

00:20:03.180 --> 00:20:05.180
a 2-by-3 grid

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:07.230
and then there's also a box

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:09.230
for special clouds

00:20:09.230 --> 00:20:11.230
that don't fit into this grid,

00:20:11.230 --> 00:20:13.950
but you can imagine a 2-by-3 grid.

00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.950
Then fundamentally there are two types

00:20:15.950 --> 00:20:18.100
of cloud families.

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:20.370
One is the cumulus cloud,

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:22.370
a cumulation,

00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:24.370
a cumulus point,

00:20:24.370 --> 00:20:26.370
an accumulation of something —

00:20:26.370 --> 00:20:28.670
these are heap clouds.

00:20:28.670 --> 00:20:30.670
Heap clouds is what they're called,

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:32.670
everything that has a cumulus-cloud form.

00:20:32.670 --> 00:20:34.670
Then there's stratus,

00:20:34.670 --> 00:20:36.670
which is a layer cloud.

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:38.670
Everything that's fog, for example,

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:40.670
is a proper layer cloud.

00:20:40.670 --> 00:20:42.670
Everything that's so nicely spread out

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:46.030
in horizontal cloud fields.

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:48.030
The two cloud families differ

00:20:48.030 --> 00:20:50.030
mainly in that cumulus clouds

00:20:50.030 --> 00:20:52.030
form primarily

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:54.030
when very strong

00:20:54.030 --> 00:20:56.030
vertical air-mass movements

00:20:56.030 --> 00:20:58.030
take place, so when a thermal rises

00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:00.030
for example, or when in high

00:21:00.030 --> 00:21:02.030
air layers an air layer is forced

00:21:02.030 --> 00:21:04.030
to rise.

00:21:04.030 --> 00:21:06.030
Then you get cumulus cloud forms.

00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:08.030
Cumulus cloud forms.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:10.030
With stratus it's the opposite.

00:21:10.030 --> 00:21:12.030
That actually points more to

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:14.030
a stable air mass,

00:21:14.030 --> 00:21:16.030
where there's little vertical motion in it,

00:21:16.030 --> 00:21:18.030
and rather a horizontal cloud,

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:20.030
that just settles in a bit.

00:21:20.030 --> 00:21:22.140
Just for understanding,

00:21:22.140 --> 00:21:25.410
what happens with these two cloud forms.

00:21:25.410 --> 00:21:27.410
On the side we have

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:29.410
storeys,

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:31.650
the various altitudes of clouds.

00:21:31.650 --> 00:21:33.650
There we have cirro-clouds.

00:21:33.650 --> 00:21:35.650
Ice crystals.

00:21:35.650 --> 00:21:37.650
That's a very high altitude.

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:40.560
They basically only consist of ice crystals.

00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:42.560
Then we have the alto storey.

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:44.560
That's a high cloud layer.

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:46.560
That's roughly between 4 and 7 kilometres.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:48.740
And then we have the ground level,

00:21:48.740 --> 00:21:50.740
where actually you only have the basic cloud families.

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:52.750
You'll see in a moment

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:54.750
where actually no additional name is added.

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:57.500
The altitudes

00:21:57.500 --> 00:21:59.500
are always relative.

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:01.500
They vary a bit.

00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:03.500
They might be 3 kilometres

00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:05.500
or 8 kilometres. It's not fixed.

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:07.500
It's not a precisely defined altitude.

00:22:07.500 --> 00:22:09.500
But what's important is that

00:22:09.500 --> 00:22:11.500
alto clouds are really clearly above

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:13.500
2000 to 3000 metres.

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.500
And cirro clouds are really above 8 kilometres.

00:22:15.500 --> 00:22:18.420
So very, very high clouds.

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:20.430
And now we can actually just start

00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:22.430
putting the names of these

00:22:22.430 --> 00:22:24.430
different clouds together.

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:26.430
You see, you just have to combine them.

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:28.430
There's cirrocumulus.

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:30.430
That's made up of these two names.

00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:32.430
Then there's cirrostratus.

00:22:32.430 --> 00:22:34.610
That's a milky soup

00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:36.610
that's very, very high up.

00:22:36.610 --> 00:22:38.610
That's usually what gives you a halo.

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:40.610
So a circular rainbow

00:22:40.610 --> 00:22:42.780
at very high altitude.

00:22:42.780 --> 00:22:44.780
That's cirrostratus.

00:22:44.780 --> 00:22:46.780
That's a layer cloud again.

00:22:46.780 --> 00:22:49.630
Then we have altocumulus

00:22:49.630 --> 00:22:51.630
and altostratus.

00:22:51.630 --> 00:22:53.630
Down below we have cumulus and stratus.

00:22:53.630 --> 00:22:55.630
Those are then just the basic forms.

00:22:55.630 --> 00:22:57.630
That's also important.

00:22:57.630 --> 00:22:59.630
Cumulus and altocumulus differ

00:22:59.630 --> 00:23:01.630
mainly in that cumulus

00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:03.630
forms through sun exposure.

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:05.630
That's really the thermal updraft,

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:07.630
as we just discussed.

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:09.630
When a colder air layer

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:11.630
pushes underneath,

00:23:11.630 --> 00:23:13.630
then the warm air layer starts to rise away

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:15.630
and forms small cumulus clouds.

00:23:15.630 --> 00:23:18.060
Everything on the left-hand side

00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:20.060
points to an unstable air stratification.

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:22.270
The air is very eager to rise.

00:23:22.270 --> 00:23:24.270
There we have unstable, stable again.

00:23:24.270 --> 00:23:27.150
Everything on the right we tend to call

00:23:27.150 --> 00:23:29.150
a stable air stratification.

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:31.150
So the air isn't very eager to rise.

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:33.150
And we tend to find

00:23:33.150 --> 00:23:35.150
more inversions

00:23:35.150 --> 00:23:37.150
with stratus clouds.

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:39.150
Those are the two cloud families.

00:23:39.150 --> 00:23:41.150
They get combined

00:23:41.150 --> 00:23:43.420
and built up from these two.

00:23:43.420 --> 00:23:45.420
It's very simple,

00:23:45.420 --> 00:23:48.080
how it can be sorted into this grid.

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:50.080
Then of course we still have a few special clouds.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:53.180
We have a few special cases too.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:55.180
One cloud in the stratus range

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:57.180
is the so-called nimbostratus.

00:23:57.180 --> 00:23:59.390
Nimbus stands for rain.

00:23:59.390 --> 00:24:01.390
So layer clouds

00:24:01.390 --> 00:24:03.390
that really rain themselves out.

00:24:03.390 --> 00:24:05.570
We often have this with a warm front

00:24:05.570 --> 00:24:07.570
or in a low-pressure area,

00:24:07.570 --> 00:24:09.570
where it's just chucking it down,

00:24:09.570 --> 00:24:11.570
where it's just raining.

00:24:11.570 --> 00:24:13.570
That's usually a nimbostratus.

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:15.570
So precipitation.

00:24:15.570 --> 00:24:18.860
Then we have cirrus clouds,

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:20.860
so without an addition.

00:24:20.860 --> 00:24:22.860
Cirrus clouds are feather clouds.

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.860
These are very high, classic feather clouds.

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:26.860
For us, for flying, they're not so relevant either.

00:24:26.860 --> 00:24:29.170
For us, for flying, that's also not so relevant.

00:24:29.170 --> 00:24:31.170
Then we have lenticularis,

00:24:31.170 --> 00:24:33.170
a really interesting cloud,

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:35.170
which we'll get into now.

00:24:35.170 --> 00:24:37.170
And for us one of the most important clouds

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:39.170
is the CB, or cumulonimbus.

00:24:39.170 --> 00:24:41.170
That's the fully developed

00:24:41.170 --> 00:24:43.600
thunderstorm cloud.

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:45.600
It flashes and thunders and rains

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:47.600
and for us is really the most dangerous.

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:49.600
It extends really

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:51.600
from the lower storey

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:53.680
up to the tropopause.

00:24:53.680 --> 00:24:55.680
We'll come to that in a moment.

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:57.860
And logically there are also

00:24:57.860 --> 00:24:59.860
lots of special clouds

00:24:59.860 --> 00:25:01.860
and detailed names

00:25:01.860 --> 00:25:03.860
you can geek out about.

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:05.860
But for you, for normal flying,

00:25:05.860 --> 00:25:07.860
what matters is just the basics — the rest doesn't really matter.

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:10.030
We don't need to go any deeper into it.

00:25:10.030 --> 00:25:13.150
On the topic of clouds

00:25:13.150 --> 00:25:15.150
there's also the degree of cloud cover,

00:25:15.150 --> 00:25:17.150
which you read again and again in the weather report

00:25:17.150 --> 00:25:19.150
or in gliding

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:21.150
in the weather report etc.

00:25:21.150 --> 00:25:23.150
There we always talk about eighths.

00:25:23.150 --> 00:25:25.580
So 8 eighths cover

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:27.580
is a closed cloud cover.

00:25:27.580 --> 00:25:29.580
We don't see any blue sky,

00:25:29.580 --> 00:25:31.920
it's all closed up.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:33.920
0 eighths, logically no clouds,

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:35.920
maybe only blue thermals,

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:37.920
if there are any thermals at all.

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:39.920
There could also be blue thermals there —

00:25:39.920 --> 00:25:41.920
we've tied it together again.

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:43.920
2 eighths is covered,

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.920
2 eighths of the sky are covered

00:25:45.920 --> 00:25:48.100
and the other 6 eighths

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:50.910
are blue and clear.

00:25:50.910 --> 00:25:52.910
And of course 4 eighths is half-cloudy.

00:25:52.910 --> 00:25:55.180
4 eighths is actually a nice cloud cover

00:25:55.180 --> 00:25:57.180
for us for thermal flying.

00:25:57.180 --> 00:25:59.180
Something between 3 and 4 eighths,

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:01.180
because we have nice cumulus clouds

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:03.180
and here we still have enough blue sky,

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:05.180
so the sun can heat up the ground,

00:26:05.180 --> 00:26:07.180
so we have nice weather,

00:26:07.180 --> 00:26:09.460
so the thermals develop.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:14.050
That's the degree of cloud cover.

00:26:14.050 --> 00:26:16.050
A really interesting cloud form,

00:26:16.050 --> 00:26:18.320
lenticularis,

00:26:18.320 --> 00:26:20.320
is probably the one most pilots know,

00:26:20.320 --> 00:26:23.360
or that you've quickly seen at some point.

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:25.360
Lenticularis actually needs

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:27.360
two or three ingredients.

00:26:27.360 --> 00:26:30.110
One is a mountain range,

00:26:30.110 --> 00:26:32.110
another is a very strong wind.

00:26:32.110 --> 00:26:34.110
Lenticularis clouds always indicate

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:36.580
a very, very strong wind.

00:26:36.580 --> 00:26:38.580
And of course we need

00:26:38.580 --> 00:26:41.360
a bit of humidity,

00:26:41.360 --> 00:26:43.360
so it can also start to condense.

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:45.470
That happens usually either

00:26:45.470 --> 00:26:47.470
directly over the mountain peaks

00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:50.060
or on the lee side of the mountain range.

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:52.060
These are rotors

00:26:52.060 --> 00:26:54.060
that put the air into a wave motion

00:26:54.060 --> 00:26:56.060
and so always,

00:26:56.060 --> 00:26:58.060
at the top of this wave motion,

00:26:58.060 --> 00:27:00.060
the rising air mass condenses,

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:02.060
such a cloud forms,

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:04.060
behind it the air sinks again,

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:07.360
it stops condensing

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:09.500
and then you get these wave clouds.

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:11.970
What's important for us to know about flying:

00:27:11.970 --> 00:27:13.970
this is a very strong wind,

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:15.970
but because the mountain range

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:17.970
always stays in the same place

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:20.340
and the waves accordingly

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:22.340
always stay in the same place,

00:27:22.340 --> 00:27:24.580
this is important for us.

00:27:24.580 --> 00:27:26.580
Just because a cloud stays in place

00:27:26.580 --> 00:27:28.880
doesn't mean there's no wind.

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:30.880
Logically.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:32.880
But you certainly know these cloud forms

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:34.960
very well by sight

00:27:34.960 --> 00:27:36.960
and for all paraglider pilots

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:38.960
they're always an alarm signal,

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:41.460
when you see lenticular clouds.

00:27:41.460 --> 00:27:43.460
Then we have a really important topic,

00:27:43.460 --> 00:27:45.460
which is the wind.

00:27:45.460 --> 00:27:47.460
That's a really important topic,

00:27:47.460 --> 00:27:51.700
which is the wind.

00:27:51.700 --> 00:27:53.970
Then we have a really important topic

00:27:53.970 --> 00:27:56.980
for paraglider pilots,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:58.980
which is thunderstorms.

00:27:58.980 --> 00:28:00.980
With thunderstorms it's like this:

00:28:00.980 --> 00:28:02.980
a thunderstorm is nothing other

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:04.980
than a cumulus cloud

00:28:04.980 --> 00:28:07.540
that has grown and keeps growing.

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:09.540
It's a really big,

00:28:09.540 --> 00:28:11.540
nasty thermal cloud.

00:28:11.540 --> 00:28:13.540
That's what makes it just as

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:15.540
dangerous for us,

00:28:15.540 --> 00:28:17.540
because of course we want to fly thermals.

00:28:17.540 --> 00:28:20.060
We fly precisely on the days

00:28:20.060 --> 00:28:22.060
on which, under certain conditions,

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:24.060
it keeps flying further.

00:28:24.060 --> 00:28:26.060
We have to be careful

00:28:26.060 --> 00:28:29.460
when the thunderstorm clouds get too big.

00:28:29.460 --> 00:28:31.460
In the morning you see the first cumulus clouds,

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:33.460
we go flying,

00:28:33.460 --> 00:28:35.760
by 11 everything's nice,

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:37.760
wonderful flying conditions.

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:40.670
Then the thunderstorm clouds

00:28:40.670 --> 00:28:42.780
or cumulus clouds get a bit bigger.

00:28:42.780 --> 00:28:44.780
They form of course with the sun.

00:28:44.780 --> 00:28:47.500
We always need the engine of the sun.

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:49.500
The engine slowly starts firing.

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:51.500
It's like an engine

00:28:51.500 --> 00:28:53.500
that slowly gets going.

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:55.500
We have to slowly get careful,

00:28:55.500 --> 00:28:57.650
when the thunderstorm clouds start

00:28:57.650 --> 00:29:00.210
to merge.

00:29:00.210 --> 00:29:02.210
We have small little clouds here

00:29:02.210 --> 00:29:04.210
and suddenly two clouds

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:06.480
merge together.

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:08.480
But we're already talking about large areas,

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:10.480
not a little puffy cloud,

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:12.660
but large clouds

00:29:12.660 --> 00:29:14.660
that span a few kilometres.

00:29:14.660 --> 00:29:16.660
As soon as the cloud base

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:18.660
starts to merge,

00:29:18.660 --> 00:29:20.700
we have to be careful.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:22.750
Especially when the cloud base

00:29:22.750 --> 00:29:24.750
also slowly gets dark.

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.750
You can imagine

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:28.900
that because of the water droplets,

00:29:28.900 --> 00:29:30.900
and at some point, when the cloud gets tall,

00:29:30.900 --> 00:29:32.900
the sun's rays almost can't get through any more.

00:29:32.900 --> 00:29:34.900
That's the point where the cloud slowly

00:29:34.900 --> 00:29:36.900
starts to appear dark,

00:29:36.900 --> 00:29:40.000
where it's also dark under the base.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
And that's the point

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
where you have to slowly start paying attention

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
and which of course has a lot to do with experience.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
How much longer am I flying?

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
How long do I stay under this cloud?

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.000
Is this already a big cloud or not?

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.020
That's really an area

00:29:54.020 --> 00:29:56.020
where you as an advanced pilot

00:29:56.020 --> 00:29:58.130
need a lot of caution.

00:29:58.130 --> 00:30:00.130
And another basic rule is,

00:30:00.130 --> 00:30:02.130
when all of a sudden everything starts lifting,

00:30:02.130 --> 00:30:04.130
now we're flying in the morning,

00:30:04.130 --> 00:30:06.130
it was always hard

00:30:06.130 --> 00:30:08.130
to find the thermal,

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:10.130
the local updrafts.

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:12.130
And then suddenly everything starts lifting.

00:30:12.130 --> 00:30:14.130
Everywhere out in the valley I can fly

00:30:14.130 --> 00:30:16.130
and it's lifting and up there is a big cloud.

00:30:16.130 --> 00:30:18.180
There you really have to start being careful.

00:30:18.180 --> 00:30:20.180
Because then the door

00:30:20.180 --> 00:30:23.200
of this thunderstorm slowly starts to run.

00:30:23.200 --> 00:30:25.200
And at some point more and more merge

00:30:25.200 --> 00:30:27.410
and they get taller and taller.

00:30:27.410 --> 00:30:29.410
And it actually doesn't even need any more energy

00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:31.410
from the sun,

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:33.410
because the engine immediately starts turning.

00:30:33.410 --> 00:30:35.410
Because warm air rises,

00:30:35.410 --> 00:30:37.410
cools down, sinks back down.

00:30:37.410 --> 00:30:39.410
Because we have cold air,

00:30:39.410 --> 00:30:41.410
the warm air just rises faster

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:43.410
and then you get a kind of chain reaction

00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:45.410
and a turbo that starts firing.

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:47.410
And the cloud doesn't always grow,

00:30:47.410 --> 00:30:49.410
but often up to the tropopause.

00:30:49.410 --> 00:30:51.580
And then you get these beautiful

00:30:51.580 --> 00:30:53.580
anvil shapes of the cloud.

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:55.580
That's when, when the thunderstorm cloud rises to the top,

00:30:55.580 --> 00:30:57.580
you can imagine,

00:30:57.580 --> 00:30:59.580
like a Perspex sheet

00:30:59.580 --> 00:31:01.580
that lies over it, where the cloud grows up to it

00:31:01.580 --> 00:31:04.980
and then can only go sideways

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:06.980
and forms the anvil.

00:31:06.980 --> 00:31:08.980
And in this phase, when the thunderstorm is fully developed,

00:31:08.980 --> 00:31:10.980
there's a lot of friction in the air mass,

00:31:10.980 --> 00:31:13.060
which sinks and rises.

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:15.060
And so sometimes there's lightning

00:31:15.060 --> 00:31:17.330
and there's mostly also precipitation.

00:31:17.330 --> 00:31:19.540
Uhm, that's it for thunderstorms.

00:31:19.540 --> 00:31:21.780
And something I'd really like

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:24.140
to lay on your heart,

00:31:24.140 --> 00:31:26.140
everyone is afraid of the thunderstorm

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:28.140
when they're under it.

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:30.140
So the climb rates are extreme,

00:31:30.140 --> 00:31:32.140
you really have to be careful there.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:34.140
Uhm, but what's even more concerning

00:31:34.140 --> 00:31:36.140
is the danger

00:31:36.140 --> 00:31:38.140
from the outflow of a thunderstorm like that.

00:31:38.140 --> 00:31:40.580
The air mass that rises and then

00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:42.580
extremely cools down up at 13,000

00:31:42.580 --> 00:31:44.980
metres up there,

00:31:44.980 --> 00:31:46.980
at some point sinks down

00:31:46.980 --> 00:31:48.980
and it's like a bucket of water that gets dumped out.

00:31:48.980 --> 00:31:51.340
And accordingly

00:31:51.340 --> 00:31:53.340
the cold air empties out

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:55.340
and it's heavy

00:31:55.340 --> 00:31:57.340
and cold, so it heads for the ground.

00:31:57.340 --> 00:31:59.520
And it can really dump out

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:01.520
and then it goes into the valleys

00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:03.520
and down to the landing zones

00:32:03.520 --> 00:32:05.520
and it can also cause very strong turbulence

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:07.570
much further away from the thunderstorm.

00:32:07.570 --> 00:32:09.570
So that's not only the danger

00:32:09.570 --> 00:32:11.680
directly under the thunderstorm,

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:13.680
but really a huge danger

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:16.180
next to the thunderstorm too.

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:18.180
Because the cold-air outflows really go in down below

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:20.180
and that makes the landing extremely turbulent

00:32:20.180 --> 00:32:22.180
and dangerous

00:32:22.180 --> 00:32:24.450
and very, very unpleasant.

00:32:24.450 --> 00:32:26.450
And the cold air or outflows can then,

00:32:26.450 --> 00:32:28.450
under certain circumstances, also trigger the next thunderstorm,

00:32:28.450 --> 00:32:30.450
where then warm air masses again —

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:32.450
which, for example, are sitting at the valley floor —

00:32:32.450 --> 00:32:34.500
the cold air mass comes down,

00:32:34.500 --> 00:32:36.500
the warm rises like the weather and then gives

00:32:36.500 --> 00:32:38.640
the next turbulence

00:32:38.640 --> 00:32:40.940
and maybe even the thunderstorm.

00:32:40.940 --> 00:32:42.940
So you really have to be careful

00:32:42.940 --> 00:32:44.940
about these cold-air outflows of the thunderstorm.

00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:46.940
It's almost more dangerous than the updraft.

00:32:46.940 --> 00:32:49.020
So the updraft is also dangerous logically,

00:32:49.020 --> 00:32:51.020
but the cold-air outflows are the ones

00:32:51.020 --> 00:32:54.830
that unfortunately many pilots underestimate again and again.

00:32:54.830 --> 00:32:56.830
When you look at it, it looks like this.

00:32:56.830 --> 00:32:58.980
When you see precipitation

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:00.980
under a cloud, then it's the last —

00:33:00.980 --> 00:33:03.170
the last,

00:33:03.170 --> 00:33:05.170
it's the ultima ratio, to land

00:33:05.170 --> 00:33:07.170
or to fly as far away as possible

00:33:07.170 --> 00:33:09.440
and then land as soon as possible.

00:33:09.440 --> 00:33:11.440
But of course when it looks like this, then it's really no longer good

00:33:11.440 --> 00:33:13.440
to fly. That's a proper outflow.

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:15.440
You can really see how the bucket of water

00:33:15.440 --> 00:33:17.440
gets dumped out and how massively

00:33:17.440 --> 00:33:19.440
cold air gets let out below.

00:33:19.440 --> 00:33:22.160
And that really causes a lot of wind.

00:33:22.160 --> 00:33:24.160
Then again, the radar, as we've already said.

00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:26.160
It's important — look at the radar,

00:33:26.160 --> 00:33:28.160
see what's happening.

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:30.160
Look at the cloud below.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:32.160
If they're clouds, you don't see how high they are up top.

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:34.160
But you might see another cloud

00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:36.160
50 kilometres away. And if that's already a huge tower,

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:38.160
then you know that maybe

00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:40.160
the cloud everywhere isn't much smaller either.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:42.560
Then with the radar it's really important —

00:33:42.560 --> 00:33:44.560
look at the radar, that's a good thing.

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:46.610
But also, keep your eyes

00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:48.780
open outside. The radar image alone is

00:33:48.780 --> 00:33:50.780
always a bit delayed and is

00:33:50.780 --> 00:33:52.780
sometimes also not exactly what

00:33:52.780 --> 00:33:54.780
is everywhere. It can develop very quickly and

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:56.780
that might sometimes not even really be visible on the radar yet.

00:33:56.780 --> 00:33:58.780
So always keep your eyes

00:33:58.780 --> 00:34:00.780
open and look at what's happening all around.

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:03.730
And what it looks like.

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:05.730
And if it's a medium-sized cloud,

00:34:05.730 --> 00:34:07.730
maybe also a little tip.

00:34:07.730 --> 00:34:09.730
If it's not yet a thunderstorm,

00:34:09.730 --> 00:34:11.840
but just a cumulus cloud you find,

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:14.020
is it already sucking, is it still good or not,

00:34:14.020 --> 00:34:16.020
then just fly along the edge of the cloud.

00:34:16.020 --> 00:34:18.020
Then you can quickly always get out of

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:20.020
this updraft zone, where you might struggle

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.160
to get back down. So better

00:34:22.160 --> 00:34:24.160
fly along the edge of the cloud. But obviously

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:26.160
with thunderstorms really be careful.

00:34:26.160 --> 00:34:28.160
That has a lot to do with know-how.

00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:30.160
And that's sometimes a bit of playing with fire,

00:34:30.160 --> 00:34:32.820
when it really comes to thunderstorms.

00:34:32.820 --> 00:34:37.470
Right. Then we come

00:34:37.470 --> 00:34:39.470
to another important chapter.

00:34:39.470 --> 00:34:42.590
The

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:44.770
valley-wind system.

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:46.770
That's a really important phenomenon that, by the way, happens in all

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:48.770
mountain ranges. Including ours

00:34:48.770 --> 00:34:50.940
in the Alps. And specifically

00:34:50.940 --> 00:34:53.250
we have again — you see,

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:55.250
we keep tying things together —

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.250
we have the sun exposure,

00:34:57.250 --> 00:34:59.360
which in mountains

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:01.360
can produce much more heat.

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:03.360
Or can warm up better

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:05.360
than in the lowlands.

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:07.600
And so the warming

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:09.600
in the alpine region produces

00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:11.810
a

00:35:11.810 --> 00:35:13.810
lower air pressure over

00:35:13.810 --> 00:35:15.810
the course of the day. And as we

00:35:15.810 --> 00:35:17.810
had it, the air mass always wants to equalise pressure.

00:35:17.810 --> 00:35:19.810
We have higher pressure

00:35:19.810 --> 00:35:21.810
in the lowlands

00:35:21.810 --> 00:35:23.920
and lower pressure

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:25.920
in the mountains. And so

00:35:25.920 --> 00:35:27.920
there's an equalising flow

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:30.450
over the course of the day.

00:35:30.450 --> 00:35:32.450
Careful, that's not to be confused with a

00:35:32.450 --> 00:35:34.450
high- or low-pressure area on an isobar chart.

00:35:34.450 --> 00:35:36.450
We see, that of course is never

00:35:36.450 --> 00:35:38.450
shown that way on an isobar chart. But we have

00:35:38.450 --> 00:35:40.450
higher pressure and lower pressure.

00:35:40.450 --> 00:35:42.450
But it's exactly the same weather phenomenon

00:35:42.450 --> 00:35:44.450
with pressure equalisation, with the

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:46.660
wind system that comes about.

00:35:46.660 --> 00:35:48.660
And so there's the equalising flow

00:35:48.660 --> 00:35:50.990
over the course of the day.

00:35:50.990 --> 00:35:52.990
It's usually strongest,

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:54.990
starting around 11 it kicks in,

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:56.990
it reaches its peak

00:35:56.990 --> 00:35:58.990
around 3 in the afternoon.

00:35:58.990 --> 00:36:00.990
And in terms of the season, it's like this:

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:02.990
in spring, as soon as

00:36:02.990 --> 00:36:05.070
the inner-alpine region

00:36:05.070 --> 00:36:07.070
slowly becomes snow-free,

00:36:07.070 --> 00:36:09.440
then it slowly starts.

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:11.440
Then it runs through into autumn.

00:36:11.440 --> 00:36:13.440
It gets weaker and weaker in summer

00:36:13.440 --> 00:36:15.490
towards autumn. But the peak time is

00:36:15.490 --> 00:36:17.660
certainly around June, I'd say.

00:36:17.660 --> 00:36:19.660
When the thermal activity is also

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:21.710
strongest. So it always needs

00:36:21.710 --> 00:36:23.710
thermal activity to trigger it.

00:36:23.710 --> 00:36:25.710
Of course if we have an overcast sky

00:36:25.710 --> 00:36:27.710
or have inversions,

00:36:27.710 --> 00:36:29.710
which don't trigger thermals, then there's

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:31.710
no real valley-wind system either.

00:36:31.710 --> 00:36:36.220
Right.

00:36:36.220 --> 00:36:38.370
And so at night

00:36:38.370 --> 00:36:40.370
you have the opposite.

00:36:40.370 --> 00:36:42.830
When a mountain wind sets in,

00:36:42.830 --> 00:36:44.830
it usually starts in the evening,

00:36:44.830 --> 00:36:47.260
around 6 it kicks in.

00:36:47.260 --> 00:36:49.260
Then we often have higher pressure

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:51.260
in the alpine region, because the mountains

00:36:51.260 --> 00:36:53.260
cool down faster than the lowlands.

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:55.380
You might know the lowlands.

00:36:55.380 --> 00:36:57.460
If you sit by the lake, it stays much longer

00:36:57.460 --> 00:36:59.460
still warm than in the mountains, when the sun

00:36:59.460 --> 00:37:01.460
slowly goes away. And so we

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:03.460
also again have a pressure difference,

00:37:03.460 --> 00:37:05.460
where we have higher pressure in the lowlands,

00:37:05.460 --> 00:37:07.460
uh, lower pressure in the lowlands,

00:37:07.460 --> 00:37:09.460
sorry. And so

00:37:09.460 --> 00:37:11.460
an equalising flow, which around 6

00:37:11.460 --> 00:37:13.570
slowly sets in.

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:15.570
And there's the phenomenon

00:37:15.570 --> 00:37:18.190
of reverse thermals,

00:37:18.190 --> 00:37:20.190
where when the cold air flows out of the mountains,

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:22.190
sometimes the slightly warmer air

00:37:22.190 --> 00:37:24.190
in the valley rises away.

00:37:24.190 --> 00:37:26.190
There's a kind of reverse thermal,

00:37:26.190 --> 00:37:28.240
a convergence that then forms,

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:30.240
usually in the middle of the valley.

00:37:30.240 --> 00:37:32.290
And sometimes

00:37:32.290 --> 00:37:34.290
at a special spot, for example Interlaken,

00:37:34.290 --> 00:37:36.290
there's a really nice updraft,

00:37:36.290 --> 00:37:38.290
where you could sometimes fly into the night,

00:37:38.290 --> 00:37:40.290
if you were allowed to.

00:37:40.290 --> 00:37:42.290
There are special weather phenomena.

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:44.290
But that's the mountain wind that sets in.

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:46.290
By the way, that's also a problem for the take-off

00:37:46.290 --> 00:37:48.290
if you have high mountains within the flying area —

00:37:48.290 --> 00:37:50.290
then sometimes there's like

00:37:50.290 --> 00:37:52.290
a switch that flips in the evening,

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:54.290
the mountain wind, and then sometimes we can hardly get

00:37:54.290 --> 00:37:56.400
away from the take-off any more. That's something you sometimes

00:37:56.400 --> 00:37:58.400
also have to factor in,

00:37:58.400 --> 00:38:00.400
that the mountain wind can also set in.

00:38:00.400 --> 00:38:03.100
Right. Then to the

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:05.100
valley wind — that's really important for you to know.

00:38:05.100 --> 00:38:07.100
The valley wind can really become a problem in spring,

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:09.100
because it can get very, very strong.

00:38:09.100 --> 00:38:11.340
And there's a great valley-wind chart

00:38:11.340 --> 00:38:13.360
from the SAV; it has a bit to do with

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:15.360
experience. Main valleys

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:17.360
you can imagine, like a root

00:38:17.360 --> 00:38:19.360
of a tree, that merges together.

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:21.360
The further into the main valley you are,

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:23.600
where this root is thick,

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:25.600
the more valley wind we have,

00:38:25.600 --> 00:38:27.600
where the main Alpine ridge really gets sucked in.

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:29.600
So the Rhine valley for example, the Rhône valley

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:31.600
and so on, those are all valleys

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:33.600
that can cause very strong valley winds.

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:35.600
Sometimes you can get 50–60 km

00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:37.600
per hour of valley wind there.

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:39.600
We're flying thermals in the Valais.

00:38:39.600 --> 00:38:41.600
If you go flying in the Valais in June,

00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:43.600
then you might have super nice thermal

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:45.600
temperatures.

00:38:45.600 --> 00:38:47.600
Up top, the valley wind, that's only in the valley,

00:38:47.600 --> 00:38:49.600
it's really in the valley floor,

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:51.780
at 500 metres above the ground, depending.

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:53.780
You can fly thermally up here and then

00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:55.780
you have to land in the valley and then

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:58.210
you have a lot of wind. And you really have

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:00.210
to think hard in the main Alpine valleys in spring

00:39:00.210 --> 00:39:02.210
about when you have to land just then,

00:39:02.210 --> 00:39:04.220
or you might even have to

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:06.220
do a top landing.

00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:08.220
That's something you really have to watch out for,

00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:10.560
when you fly in the main Alpine valleys.

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:12.560
There are also still some special phenomena

00:39:12.560 --> 00:39:14.610
like up at Maloja.

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:16.610
Those are valley winds that spill over,

00:39:16.610 --> 00:39:18.610
spill over the pass and then

00:39:18.610 --> 00:39:20.610
fall down behind it and also cause very turbulent

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:22.620
air conditions.

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:24.640
Those are very local phenomena,

00:39:24.640 --> 00:39:26.640
but you have to inform yourself,

00:39:26.640 --> 00:39:28.640
if for example you're flying up at the Grimsel

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:31.070
or at Maloja. You should

00:39:31.070 --> 00:39:33.150
really be careful.

00:39:33.150 --> 00:39:35.150
So if you fly there, inform yourself

00:39:35.150 --> 00:39:37.150
about the valley-wind systems. What's important for your

00:39:37.150 --> 00:39:39.150
theory exam is, you have to know

00:39:39.150 --> 00:39:41.150
when the valley winds come about

00:39:41.150 --> 00:39:43.150
and what times they are.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:45.150
That's actually what you want to be quizzed on here.

00:39:45.150 --> 00:39:47.150
And something you always have to factor in.

00:39:47.150 --> 00:39:50.990
Right. Then we come

00:39:50.990 --> 00:39:52.990
to another weather phenomenon

00:39:52.990 --> 00:39:54.990
that's super, super important for paraglider pilots.

00:39:54.990 --> 00:39:57.260
And that's the Foehn.

00:39:57.260 --> 00:40:00.180
I always say there are three main dangers

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:02.180
for pilots. It's thunderstorms,

00:40:02.180 --> 00:40:04.400
it's the Foehn, and probably

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:06.400
valley winds.

00:40:06.400 --> 00:40:08.700
That's another chapter. Because with all

00:40:08.700 --> 00:40:10.700
the other weather phenomena, you have strong wind

00:40:10.700 --> 00:40:12.700
at the take-off. If a west wind comes,

00:40:12.700 --> 00:40:15.070
then you have a really full

00:40:15.070 --> 00:40:17.070
west wind at the take-off and then you notice

00:40:17.070 --> 00:40:19.070
that maybe it's not such a good idea to launch,

00:40:19.070 --> 00:40:21.070
when you have mega wind and you're already struggling,

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:23.070
to get up to launch. Foehn,

00:40:23.070 --> 00:40:25.630
thunderstorms and valley wind,

00:40:25.630 --> 00:40:27.630
those are actually the only weather phenomena

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:29.630
where on the one side the

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:31.630
flying weather can change extremely quickly —

00:40:31.630 --> 00:40:33.630
so it can get very turbulent very quickly —

00:40:33.630 --> 00:40:35.630
and on the other side they are

00:40:35.630 --> 00:40:37.630
usually also strongest at the landing zone below.

00:40:37.630 --> 00:40:39.630
So it can be that you

00:40:39.630 --> 00:40:41.630
launch in the valley wind on the mountain above

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:43.630
and have calm conditions, and in the valley below

00:40:43.630 --> 00:40:45.630
it's hammering and there's really mega wind.

00:40:45.630 --> 00:40:47.630
With Foehn the phenomenon is

00:40:47.630 --> 00:40:50.670
exactly the same. So a feeling

00:40:50.670 --> 00:40:52.670
for the Foehn — how does it come about,

00:40:52.670 --> 00:40:54.910
how much of a wind system,

00:40:54.910 --> 00:40:56.910
as we've had it, a pressure equalisation.

00:40:56.910 --> 00:40:58.910
We need a pressure difference,

00:40:58.910 --> 00:41:00.910
so we need two ingredients for Foehn.

00:41:00.910 --> 00:41:02.910
We need a pressure difference

00:41:02.910 --> 00:41:05.540
and we need a big mountain range.

00:41:05.540 --> 00:41:08.000
That is to say, Foehn

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.000
exists in all regions of the world.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.000
It's in the Himalayas, in the Andes,

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.530
in the Pyrenees

00:41:14.530 --> 00:41:16.530
and here in the Alps.

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:18.530
The Foehn has a different name in each place;

00:41:18.530 --> 00:41:20.530
there isn't really a name

00:41:20.530 --> 00:41:22.770
that's the same all around the world.

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:25.040
In the Alps the name 'Foehn' has established itself,

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:27.040
and there's a North Foehn and a

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:29.040
South Foehn, so it goes in both

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:31.090
directions of course, back and forth.

00:41:31.090 --> 00:41:33.090
For us now on the northern side of the Alps,

00:41:33.090 --> 00:41:35.090
of course the South Foehn is the one that causes problems.

00:41:35.090 --> 00:41:37.900
Now in this case we have Ticino on the left,

00:41:37.900 --> 00:41:39.900
on the right we have the German lowlands

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:42.690
or our pre-Alps.

00:41:42.690 --> 00:41:44.690
We have higher pressure on the southern side of the Alps

00:41:44.690 --> 00:41:46.690
than on the northern side.

00:41:46.690 --> 00:41:48.690
Accordingly,

00:41:48.690 --> 00:41:50.690
the air mass wants to equalise the pressure

00:41:50.690 --> 00:41:52.690
and flows

00:41:52.690 --> 00:41:54.690
over the mountain ridge.

00:41:54.690 --> 00:41:56.960
With Foehn maybe still important is,

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:58.960
that depending on the situation

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:00.960
the Foehn gets really sucked in

00:42:00.960 --> 00:42:02.960
from the lowlands. You can imagine,

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:04.960
like a vacuum cleaner that pulls air in from behind.

00:42:04.960 --> 00:42:06.960
And this air

00:42:06.960 --> 00:42:08.960
really wedges into the valleys

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:10.960
and depending on meteorological conditions

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:12.960
really wedges all the way down to the valley floor

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:14.960
and can cause very, very strong winds

00:42:14.960 --> 00:42:17.230
down in the valley. There are sometimes special

00:42:17.230 --> 00:42:19.230
weather situations where there isn't always much wind

00:42:19.230 --> 00:42:21.230
at the take-off, but in a Foehn valley

00:42:21.230 --> 00:42:24.430
there's extremely strong wind.

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:26.430
Of course that's what makes it dangerous for us on the northern side of the Alps,

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:28.770
because with Foehn

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:30.770
we usually have lots of sun,

00:42:30.770 --> 00:42:32.770
beautiful weather, blue skies, everything is nice,

00:42:32.770 --> 00:42:34.770
it would actually be super beautiful for flying,

00:42:34.770 --> 00:42:36.770
it would also always be really tempting.

00:42:36.770 --> 00:42:38.770
But that's also what makes it just as dangerous with Foehn,

00:42:38.770 --> 00:42:40.770
that it comes about precisely in such nice-looking weather.

00:42:40.770 --> 00:42:43.580
It comes about, in such a nice weather pattern.

00:42:43.580 --> 00:42:45.580
And specifically the air mass rises

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:48.370
in this case on the southern side of the Alps,

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:50.580
it condenses —

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:52.580
we have it again, the air mass rises,

00:42:52.580 --> 00:42:54.580
it condenses, forms a cloud,

00:42:54.580 --> 00:42:56.780
under certain circumstances it even rains out

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:58.900
and it goes over the main

00:42:58.900 --> 00:43:00.900
Alpine ridge, forms a so-called

00:43:00.900 --> 00:43:02.900
Foehn wall — that's really like a wall

00:43:02.900 --> 00:43:04.900
that follows the main Alpine ridge.

00:43:04.900 --> 00:43:07.070
It wedges down,

00:43:07.070 --> 00:43:09.310
dries out,

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.310
it dissolves the clouds and the dry

00:43:11.310 --> 00:43:13.310
warm wind wedges into the lowlands,

00:43:13.310 --> 00:43:15.310
into the Alpine valleys

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:17.310
and of course causes very, very strong

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:19.310
turbulence and downdrafts and wind shear

00:43:19.310 --> 00:43:21.310
and also the lee rotors,

00:43:21.310 --> 00:43:23.310
which under certain circumstances can also form

00:43:23.310 --> 00:43:25.310
the lenticularis clouds.

00:43:25.310 --> 00:43:28.000
Important: Foehn

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.430
doesn't always have to cause rain

00:43:30.430 --> 00:43:32.430
in the south, or always have to cause

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:34.430
lenticularis.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:36.430
Foehn can sometimes be dry

00:43:36.430 --> 00:43:38.430
and not show the cloud forms.

00:43:38.430 --> 00:43:40.430
That's just the classic Foehn,

00:43:40.430 --> 00:43:42.430
how it really usually forms,

00:43:42.430 --> 00:43:45.470
when there's a nice damming cloud.

00:43:45.470 --> 00:43:48.860
So the pressure difference is mainly important.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:51.870
On the isobar chart

00:43:51.870 --> 00:43:53.870
it looks something like this —

00:43:53.870 --> 00:43:55.870
if you look at the rings,

00:43:55.870 --> 00:43:57.870
if we had no mountains,

00:43:57.870 --> 00:43:59.870
then they would just continue around here,

00:43:59.870 --> 00:44:01.870
and just distribute air pressure

00:44:01.870 --> 00:44:03.870
evenly.

00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:05.870
But now we have the

00:44:05.870 --> 00:44:07.870
mountain ridge, the main Alpine ridge,

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:09.870
and you see in the Smali

00:44:09.870 --> 00:44:11.870
in the isobars a kink

00:44:11.870 --> 00:44:14.080
at the main Alpine ridge,

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:16.080
the so-called Foehn knee, as it's called.

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:18.080
So if you see a kink on an isobar chart

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:20.130
over a mountain range,

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:22.140
really a massive kink,

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:24.140
then it usually has something to do with Foehn,

00:44:24.140 --> 00:44:26.140
then you have to start being careful.

00:44:26.140 --> 00:44:28.140
And again, as we had it,

00:44:28.140 --> 00:44:30.140
where the isobars are closer together,

00:44:30.140 --> 00:44:32.140
we have a lot of wind.

00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:34.670
Which in this case

00:44:34.670 --> 00:44:36.670
ahead of this cold front

00:44:36.670 --> 00:44:38.780
brings the Foehn.

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:40.990
By the way, that's a weather phenomenon

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:43.680
that often happens in Switzerland

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:45.680
before a cold front arrives.

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:47.680
But really important: it doesn't always have to be

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:49.680
ahead of a cold front,

00:44:49.680 --> 00:44:51.920
you can also get Foehn

00:44:51.920 --> 00:44:53.920
without a cold front coming.

00:44:53.920 --> 00:44:56.220
But the classic is,

00:44:56.220 --> 00:44:58.220
a cold front approaches from the west,

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:00.400
a Foehn knee forms,

00:45:00.400 --> 00:45:03.440
you get a Foehn flow

00:45:03.440 --> 00:45:06.480
and at some point the front breaks through.

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:08.480
There's a Foehn diagram,

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:10.480
there are various providers,

00:45:10.480 --> 00:45:12.480
there's a Foehn diagram,

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:14.480
from the SAV on the MeteoSwiss site,

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:16.480
where we have access,

00:45:16.480 --> 00:45:18.480
really very good displays.

00:45:18.480 --> 00:45:20.530
This is from the MeteoSwiss Foehn diagram,

00:45:20.530 --> 00:45:22.530
where we have in the middle the 0 hPa line,

00:45:22.530 --> 00:45:24.530
we always talk about the pressure difference,

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:26.530
when we have an air-pressure station,

00:45:26.530 --> 00:45:28.530
a barometer in Ticino

00:45:28.530 --> 00:45:30.900
and a barometer in Zurich for example,

00:45:30.900 --> 00:45:32.900
and you measure the pressure difference there,

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:34.900
then you also know

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:36.900
whether there could be a balancing flow on one side

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:40.030
or on the other side.

00:45:40.030 --> 00:45:42.030
As a rule of thumb, you see the dashed line,

00:45:42.030 --> 00:45:44.030
we talk about 4 hPa.

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:46.240
If the

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:48.740
curve swings up,

00:45:48.740 --> 00:45:50.940
above 4 hPa,

00:45:50.940 --> 00:45:52.940
we talk about South Foehn;

00:45:52.940 --> 00:45:54.940
below we talk about North Foehn —

00:45:54.940 --> 00:45:56.940
for example here on Saturday and on Friday night

00:45:56.940 --> 00:45:59.380
we'd talk more about North Foehn.

00:45:59.380 --> 00:46:01.380
And that's very unsettled weather in this forecast,

00:46:01.380 --> 00:46:03.380
the pressure swings extremely back and forth

00:46:03.380 --> 00:46:05.380
and that always actually means a lot of wind,

00:46:05.380 --> 00:46:07.380
lots of motion in the air

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:09.380
and as a rule no good flying weather.

00:46:09.380 --> 00:46:12.060
Now it's also important for you to know

00:46:12.060 --> 00:46:14.270
that you really read the weather reports well

00:46:14.270 --> 00:46:16.270
and that you're aware that the Foehn

00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:18.270
sometimes breaks through at 4 hPa.

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:20.270
Sometimes you can also

00:46:20.270 --> 00:46:22.270
still fly at 8 hPa,

00:46:22.270 --> 00:46:24.270
that's not to be recommended for anybody

00:46:24.270 --> 00:46:26.270
and it really has a lot to do with experience

00:46:26.270 --> 00:46:28.270
and you also have to know the area very well.

00:46:28.270 --> 00:46:31.490
And I really wouldn't recommend

00:46:31.490 --> 00:46:33.490
flying in Foehn conditions.

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:35.490
You always hear things like:

00:46:35.490 --> 00:46:37.490
I've flown at 8 hPa

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:39.490
in this and that flying area

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:41.490
and it was no problem at all.

00:46:41.490 --> 00:46:43.490
It can sometimes break doors down,

00:46:43.490 --> 00:46:45.500
sometimes not break doors down.

00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:47.500
It has a lot to do

00:46:47.500 --> 00:46:49.500
with what direction the Foehn comes from.

00:46:49.500 --> 00:46:51.500
It can sometimes be southwesterly,

00:46:51.500 --> 00:46:53.500
it can sometimes be a southeasterly Foehn.

00:46:53.500 --> 00:46:55.500
That has to do with the temperature stratifications in the air.

00:46:55.500 --> 00:46:57.500
It would blow the lecture wide open.

00:46:57.500 --> 00:46:59.500
About Foehn you could talk for 2 hours

00:46:59.500 --> 00:47:01.710
and philosophise.

00:47:01.710 --> 00:47:03.710
What's also important is, if there's a Foehn tendency

00:47:03.710 --> 00:47:05.710
around, that you really think hard,

00:47:05.710 --> 00:47:07.710
whether you really want to go flying.

00:47:07.710 --> 00:47:09.710
And the Foehn has already

00:47:09.710 --> 00:47:11.710
caught out a pilot before.

00:47:11.710 --> 00:47:13.710
It can really vary a lot.

00:47:13.710 --> 00:47:15.710
That's really important.

00:47:15.710 --> 00:47:17.710
Also about this curve.

00:47:17.710 --> 00:47:19.710
Just because it's at 4 hPa,

00:47:19.710 --> 00:47:23.230
doesn't mean there can't be any Foehn.

00:47:23.230 --> 00:47:25.230
That's why it's also in Meteo practice,

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:27.230
which we look at in another course,

00:47:27.230 --> 00:47:29.390
really important to do with

00:47:29.390 --> 00:47:31.390
you looking at wind measurements,

00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:33.390
knowing the area well,

00:47:33.390 --> 00:47:35.390
looking at the pressure charts,

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:37.390
comparing the forecast values

00:47:37.390 --> 00:47:39.390
with reality,

00:47:39.390 --> 00:47:41.390
with the actually measured values on the day.

00:47:41.390 --> 00:47:43.390
That's all from a computer model.

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:45.390
It doesn't all have to come true that way.

00:47:45.390 --> 00:47:47.390
They can also be a bit off.

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:49.390
That has a lot to do with experience.

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:52.850
So be careful with Foehn.

00:47:52.850 --> 00:47:54.850
With Foehn it's the case

00:47:54.850 --> 00:47:57.060
that the air mass, like water,

00:47:57.060 --> 00:47:59.060
like all gases,

00:47:59.060 --> 00:48:01.330
wants to take the path of least resistance.

00:48:01.330 --> 00:48:03.330
Accordingly, valleys

00:48:03.330 --> 00:48:05.330
that are oriented south to north,

00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:07.330
like for example the Rhine valley,

00:48:07.330 --> 00:48:09.330
are much more Foehn-prone

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:11.330
than a valley that runs crosswise.

00:48:11.330 --> 00:48:13.330
So the air mass

00:48:13.330 --> 00:48:15.330
will come from the southern side

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:17.330
somehow onto the northern side of the Alps,

00:48:17.330 --> 00:48:19.330
now in the case of South Foehn.

00:48:19.330 --> 00:48:21.330
Accordingly there are special Foehn areas,

00:48:21.330 --> 00:48:23.330
where you have to be especially careful.

00:48:23.330 --> 00:48:25.330
Inform yourselves at the clubs,

00:48:25.330 --> 00:48:27.330
at the flight schools, in the flying area,

00:48:27.330 --> 00:48:29.330
on various websites,

00:48:29.330 --> 00:48:31.330
where you find this information,

00:48:31.330 --> 00:48:33.330
whether certain areas are Foehn-prone or not.

00:48:33.330 --> 00:48:35.700
And really be conservative,

00:48:35.700 --> 00:48:37.700
when it comes to Foehn areas.

00:48:37.700 --> 00:48:39.840
There you see such a map,

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:41.840
you also find it at the SAV — it's really good.

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:43.840
That thing, to inform yourself with.

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:48.060
Here we have the last slide,

00:48:48.060 --> 00:48:50.240
Foehn images, just

00:48:50.240 --> 00:48:52.240
so that you've also seen it visually.

00:48:52.240 --> 00:48:54.240
We have the beautiful lenticularis clouds

00:48:54.240 --> 00:48:56.240
and we have a Foehn wall,

00:48:56.240 --> 00:48:58.240
that's really like such a beautiful wall,

00:48:58.240 --> 00:49:00.240
that forms like a claw

00:49:00.240 --> 00:49:02.270
and the air mass that sinks down behind it,

00:49:02.270 --> 00:49:04.270
which dries out.

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:06.270
And sometimes you really clearly

00:49:06.270 --> 00:49:08.270
and clearly see that on the main Alpine ridge

00:49:08.270 --> 00:49:10.270
a proper Foehn wall forms.

00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:12.270
And if you see such a cloud,

00:49:12.270 --> 00:49:14.270
that's never a good thing for flying

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:16.270
and will always cause turbulent winds,

00:49:16.270 --> 00:49:18.270
when we talk about Foehn or otherwise also

00:49:18.270 --> 00:49:21.120
strong wind.

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:24.260
Important, as I said, Foehn

00:49:24.260 --> 00:49:26.260
doesn't always have to come together with these cloud forms.

00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:28.260
It can also be a blue sky

00:49:28.260 --> 00:49:30.260
and have no clouds and be Foehn.

00:49:30.260 --> 00:49:32.820
That's important for you to know.

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:34.820
Now you've really discussed the three main dangers.

00:49:34.820 --> 00:49:36.860
discussed.

00:49:36.860 --> 00:49:39.140
We've covered the theory material,

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:41.140
because it's important for the theory exam.

00:49:41.140 --> 00:49:43.140
I'd really also like to

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:45.140
lay it on your heart firmly,

00:49:45.140 --> 00:49:47.140
to fly with the theory with open eyes,

00:49:47.140 --> 00:49:49.140
to really engage with these topics,

00:49:49.140 --> 00:49:51.140
to study these theory topics again and again

00:49:51.140 --> 00:49:53.140
and especially, really important, in flight practice

00:49:53.140 --> 00:49:55.140
to keep engaging with this topic.

00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:57.140
to keep engaging with this topic.

00:49:57.140 --> 00:49:59.140
Why do these clouds form now?

00:49:59.140 --> 00:50:01.140
Why do I have wind now?

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:03.280
Why was it different now

00:50:03.280 --> 00:50:05.280
than I expected?

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:07.280
Also look at the meteo forecasts,

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:09.280
which we also look at in another part,

00:50:09.280 --> 00:50:11.280
how exactly you make a meteo forecast.

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:13.280
Engage with it,

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:15.280
talk to your flight instructor as much as you can.

00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:17.280
Pester them during your training.

00:50:17.280 --> 00:50:20.050
Also ask flying colleagues,

00:50:20.050 --> 00:50:22.050
exchange your know-how,

00:50:22.050 --> 00:50:24.050
also ask locals,

00:50:24.050 --> 00:50:26.050
if you ever go anywhere who wants to travel,

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:28.050
for example wants to fly on an island.

00:50:28.050 --> 00:50:30.050
Talk a lot with the locals about the weather phenomena

00:50:30.050 --> 00:50:32.050
and you'll see, the more you learn here

00:50:32.050 --> 00:50:34.050
and start to understand the principles,

00:50:34.050 --> 00:50:36.050
us above all in practice

00:50:36.050 --> 00:50:38.050
can put into action and see,

00:50:38.050 --> 00:50:40.050
it works more and more,

00:50:40.050 --> 00:50:42.050
that you've made the right forecast,

00:50:42.050 --> 00:50:44.050
that you've flown to the right spot,

00:50:44.050 --> 00:50:46.050
where you expected the thermal,

00:50:46.050 --> 00:50:48.050
where you've made the right decisions,

00:50:48.050 --> 00:50:50.050
the more it also starts to be fun

00:50:50.050 --> 00:50:52.050
and I think especially meteorology

00:50:52.050 --> 00:50:54.050
is really a very motivating topic

00:50:54.050 --> 00:50:56.050
to put into action from theory into practice

00:50:56.050 --> 00:50:58.050
and a lot of fun

00:50:58.050 --> 00:51:00.770
and above all to be able to fly safely.

00:51:00.770 --> 00:51:02.770
Right.

00:51:02.770 --> 00:51:04.770
I now really wish you very nice flights,

00:51:04.770 --> 00:51:06.770
learn well here, look in,

00:51:06.770 --> 00:51:08.770
watch the videos again,

00:51:08.770 --> 00:51:10.770
we also look forward to your feedback

00:51:10.770 --> 00:51:12.770
and we wish you very nice flights

00:51:12.770 --> 00:51:14.770
and a good time.

00:51:14.770 --> 00:51:17.070
Bye.

